and without needing usb-serial-for-android locally (uses maven). It's mostly
removing the .idea files and the breaking DSL changes when the android plugin went 1.0.

title: SyncManager: Partial rewrite for better error handling.
message:
SyncManager: Partial rewrite for better error handling.

- Requests are posted in an event driven fashion with single
short-lived one-shot Runnables, rather than using a long-running
polling background thread.

- Requests are only written to disk when they cannot be posted
immediately.

- Thermo requests are never written to disk; the data is not
considered important enough to save when offline.
May revisit this if there enough interest.

- ConnectivityManager is consulted for connectivity before
performing some operations.  This will cut down on spurious
errors in the logs.

title: Manage all authentication through AuthenticationActivity.
message:
Manage all authentication through AuthenticationActivity.

In the prior design, AuthenticationActivity was started asynchronously,
showing authenticating/failure status in response to broadcasts.  Meanwhile,
AuthenticationManager/FlowManager could have started a flow and also the
PourInProgressActivity.

This was excessively asynchronous, and caused problems like issue #41, where
the duration between "authenticating" and "authenticated" was so brief that
the (single top) "authenticating" dialog wasn't displayed by the framework
until *after* the PourInProgress activity had finished.

The new design is also much simpler to follow: AuthenticatingActivity starts,
shows the progress bar, and interacts with (synchronous) AuthenticationManager
apis until the auth status is resolved, at which point it starts the flows
and finishes itself.

There is also now room for the AuthActivity to implement more elaborate UIs
during authentication (for instance, prompting for a pin).

Closes issue #41.

title: Activate the currently focused tap (only) on ambiguous auth events.
message:
Activate the currently focused tap (only) on ambiguous auth events.

In the former behavior, two flows would be started (and both valves opened, if
present) whenever an ambiguous authentication event such as RFID swipe occurred.
Users have reported this as confusing, since after finishing the desired flow,
another flow will typically be dangling in the UI.

Solution for now is to only start a single flow; guess the desired flow based
on the currently-focused tap on the home screen.

This is probably good enough for >90th percentile use cases; most people
probably don't pour from two taps at once..

CoreActivity: don't bind to core service, instead just start it if needed.

The dangling binds didn't serve much point, except to keep the service active.
This makes it difficult to stop in the background.

title: Final devious hacks for the night.
message:
Final devious hacks for the night.

- Tap status shows several fun info boxes.
- Added "ConfigurationManager", for caching API-gleaned information about the
  system.  (Eventually, Configuration should be a first-class API message.)
- Moved broadcasts into KegtapBroadcast.

title: A bunch of changes all over the place.
message:
A bunch of changes all over the place.

Major ones:
  - changed the main activity layout/fragments; now there's a single major
    TapStatusFragment, a smaller EventListFragment, and a to-be-implemented
    COntrolsFragment.
  - updated protos due to recent API changes
  - updated KegbotApi[Impl] to allow a user to log in
  - updated preferences to take a url+username+password rather than choices.
    (we could replaced/augment the URL entry with an auto-populated list)
  - added skeletal "kegerator" preferences, for selecting kegerator control
    mechanism (default = none).
